const OCR_P2_03_EXTRACT = `Miss Havisham sat in her chair as she had sat, it seemed, for decades — upright, rigid, magnificent in her ruin. The wedding dress, once white, had yellowed to the colour of old bone. It hung from her wasted frame like a shroud, its lace torn and trailing, its silk spotted with the brown stains of age. On her feet were white satin shoes, and on her head a veil of the same material, beneath which her grey hair hung in thin, disordered strands. She was, Estella thought, the most terrible thing she had ever seen — not because she was ugly, but because she was the visible monument of a grief that had consumed everything, including the person who felt it.

The room matched its occupant. The great table, once set for a wedding breakfast, was thick with dust and cobwebs. The cake — that impossible cake — had collapsed into a grey mound from which mice had long since excavated tunnels and chambers. Candles stood in their holders, burned to stumps. The clocks had stopped. Everything in this room had stopped, frozen at the exact moment when Miss Havisham's heart had broken, and everything had been left to rot as proof that time, for her, had ended.

"Come closer," Miss Havisham said. Her voice was dry and cracked, like paper that has been folded too many times. "Let me look at you."

Estella crossed the room, her footsteps muffled by the thick layer of dust on the floor. She was seventeen, and she had learned in this house to be beautiful and cold and cruel, and she did not yet understand the cost of these lessons.`

